  <li><strong>Decode the Quality Pyramid Through DOCG vs DOC Classifications</strong> - Prosecco di Conegliano e Valdobbiadene DOCG represents the apex, with stricter yield limits (13.5 tons/hectare vs 18 for DOC) and hand-harvesting requirements that create more concentrated flavors. These bottles typically show greater complexity with notes of white peach and acacia honey, while standard DOC Prosecco offers bright apple and citrus character. The DOCG versions age better and justify their 40-60% price premium through superior terroir expression.</li>

  <li><strong>Match Sweetness Levels to Your Occasion and Food Pairings</strong> - Brut Nature (0-3g/L residual sugar) pairs brilliantly with raw oysters and crudo, while Extra Dry (12-17g/L) - despite its name being sweeter than Brut - complements spicy Asian cuisine and fruit-based desserts. The higher sugar content in Extra Dry actually helps balance heat and enhances the wine's fruit-forward character, making it more versatile than many assume.</li>

  <li><strong>Serve Prosecco at 42-46°F for Optimal Bubble Expression</strong> - Unlike Champagne which can handle slightly warmer temperatures, Prosecco's Charmat method bubbles are larger and more delicate. Serving too cold (below 40°F) masks the fruit aromatics, while too warm (above 50°F) causes rapid CO2 loss. Use an ice bucket for 15-20 minutes rather than over-chilling in the refrigerator, which can mute the characteristic pear and green apple notes.</li>

  <li><strong>Choose Your Glass Shape Based on Prosecco Style</strong> - Flutes work well for basic DOC Prosecco to concentrate the bubbles and aromatics, but superior DOCG bottles deserve white wine glasses with a wider bowl. The increased surface area allows the more complex terroir-driven flavors to develop, particularly the mineral notes from the limestone-rich soils of Conegliano and Valdobbiadene. Avoid coupe glasses which dissipate the essential effervescence too quickly.</li>

