<h2>Aging & Cellaring</h2>

<p>Unlike many still wines, <strong>prosecco is crafted for immediate enjoyment</strong>, with aging potential varying dramatically across quality levels. Understanding these differences is crucial for maximizing your investment in different prosecco styles.</p>

<h3>Aging Potential by Quality Level</h3>

<p><strong>Prosecco DOC</strong> should be consumed within 18-24 months of purchase, as the Glera grape's delicate floral aromatics fade quickly. <strong>Prosecco DOCG Conegliano Valdobbiadene</strong> offers more structure, aging gracefully for 3-5 years, developing honeyed notes and increased minerality from the steep hillside vineyards' calcareous soils.</p>

<p><strong>Cartizze DOCG</strong>, prosecco's most prestigious designation, can evolve beautifully for 5-8 years, gaining complexity as primary peach and apple flavors integrate with subtle yeast autolysis characteristics. Vintage proseccos, particularly from exceptional producers like Bisol or Nino Franco, may improve for up to a decade.</p>

<h3>Storage Requirements</h3>

<p>Store prosecco bottles <strong>horizontally at 50-55°F (10-13°C)</strong> with 70% humidity. Unlike Champagne, prosecco's tank fermentation method produces less protective lees contact, making proper storage critical to prevent premature oxidation.</p>

<h3>Evolution and Peak Windows</h3>

<p>Quality prosecco evolves from bright citrus and white flower notes toward <strong>richer stone fruit and mineral complexity</strong>. The finest examples develop subtle brioche notes from extended lees contact during secondary fermentation.</p>

<p><strong>Drink Prosecco DOC within 2 years</strong>, Prosecco DOCG at 2-4 years, and reserve Cartizze for special occasions within 5-7 years of vintage.</p>

<h3>Aging vs Spoilage Signs</h3>

<p>Proper aging brings <strong>integrated bubbles, deeper golden color, and enhanced minerality</strong>. Spoilage appears as flat bubbles, browning beyond pale gold, or vinegar-like acetaldehyde aromas. Trust your palate—fresh prosecco should always maintain vibrant acidity and clean fruit expression.</p>

